# hotbar_place.tas — Hotbar selection + right-click place regression.
#
# Purpose: Verify that
#   (1) the hotbar UI is rendered persistently along the bottom of the
#       screen on the HUD layer (default slot 1=stone, 2=grass, 3=dirt),
#   (2) pressing a number key (1..0) updates `state.hotbar_selected`,
#   (3) right-clicking with a non-empty selected slot calls
#       `World.setBlock` at the face the player is looking at, and
#   (4) the placement guard refuses to drop a block inside the player's
#       AABB (verified manually — see notes below; this script focuses on
#       the happy path because TAS scripts can't easily assert "no block
#       was placed").
#
# Scene layout (flatland, deterministic spawn):
#   - Player spawns standing on the flat Y=63 plane.
#   - We look down ~30° so the raycast first hits the ground a few blocks
#     in front of the player. The placement face is the +Y face of that
#     ground block, so the new block lands on top of the floor a couple
#     blocks ahead — well outside the player AABB.
#   - With slot 1 = stone (default), the placed block has the stone
#     palette colour and a procedural texel-hash pattern. A pixel diff
#     against a baseline run captured BEFORE the right-click (or against
#     a `--hotbar=off` run that simply skips the right-click) shows the
#     newly added stone block as a small contiguous patch in front of the
#     crosshair.
#
# Usage (from utils/swindowzig):
#   zig build native -Dexample=voxel
#   ./zig-out/bin/voxel --world=flatland --aa=none \
#     --tas examples/voxel/tests/hotbar_place.tas \
#     --dump-frame=/tmp/hotbar_place.ppm
#
#   # Baseline — same scene WITHOUT firing the right-click. Compare the
#   # two PPMs; the diff should be the stone block appearing on top of
#   # the floor in front of the player and the hotbar's selected-border
#   # highlight shifting to slot 1 (which it already is by default).
#   #
#   # The simplest baseline is a copy of this script with the
#   # `mouse_down right` / `mouse_up right` lines removed; or render the
#   # exact same TAS with `--hotbar=off` AND comment out the right-click
#   # to confirm the hotbar UI itself is what's drawn at the bottom.
#
# Player-AABB guard verification (manual): edit the look-down magnitude
# below to a near-vertical pitch (`mouse_move 0 400` like dig_relight),
# then add a `mouse_down right` / `mouse_up right` pair and the engine
# logs `Hotbar: refused place at (...) — would clip player AABB` instead
# of mutating the world.
#
# Tick numbering is relative to the first post-loading tick.

# --- Capture mouse ---
1 mouse_down left
2 mouse_up left

# --- Look down ~30° so the raycast hits the ground a few blocks ahead.
#     180 mouse-delta-y ≈ 30° at the default 0.0033 rad/pixel sensitivity.
#     Same value used by ao_corners.tas. ---
3 mouse_move 0 180

# --- Select slot 1 (stone). It's already the default selection but we
#     press the key explicitly so the test exercises the keybind path. ---
8 keydown 1
9 keyup 1

# --- Right-click to place a stone block on top of the targeted ground
#     block. The press edge fires the placement; the release edge is a
#     no-op for the place handler but kept for symmetry with how SDL
#     surfaces real trackpad clicks. ---
14 mouse_down right
15 mouse_up right

# --- Hold steady so --dump-frame lands on a stable view. The mesh-dirty
#     pass after the place takes one tick to flush; we leave a generous
#     window so the dumped frame includes the new block. ---
30 mouse_move 0 0
